From 01765b8d675d1b50b741272f94adfb91755d92ed Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Wed, 25 Mar 2026 06:57:17 +0100
Subject: [PATCH 042/174] =?UTF-8?q?PGCL:=20unify=20set=5Fptes=20nr=20conve?=
 =?UTF-8?q?ntion=20=E2=80=94=20nr=20always=20means=20PTE/MMUPAGE=20count?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Fix arm64 use-after-free crash (POISON_FREE in __rmqueue_pcplist) caused
by ambiguous set_ptes nr semantics. Previously, THP split passed kernel
page count (HPAGE_PMD_NR) while folio_pte_batch returned MMUPAGE count,
and arch set_ptes multiplied nr by PAGE_MMUCOUNT internally. On arm64,
where folio_pte_batch can return >1 for PGCL sub-pages, this caused
double-expansion: 32 PTEs became 512, exhausting folio refcount and
corrupting the PCP free list.

New convention: set_ptes nr is ALWAYS the PTE/MMUPAGE count. No arch
multiplies internally. THP split passes HPAGE_PMD_MMUNR (512 on x86_64/
arm64 with MMUSHIFT=4). All arch set_ptes implementations use flat
MMUPAGE-stepping loops instead of nested kernel-page/sub-page loops.

Changes:
- include/linux/pgtable.h: generic PGCL set_ptes flat loop
- include/linux/huge_mm.h: add HPAGE_PMD_MMUNR macro
- mm/huge_memory.c: THP split uses HPAGE_PMD_MMUNR, PGCL rmap fixup
  for per-page _mapcount and folio_large_mapcount
- mm/memory.c: remove stale PGCL rmap fixup in set_pte_range
- mm/migrate_device.c: RSS counter uses HPAGE_PMD_MMUNR
- arch/{sparc,parisc,mips,powerpc}: flat MMUPAGE-stepping set_ptes
- fs/splice.c: iter_to_pipe MMUPAGE-granular GUP page tracking

Verified: 9 arches boot and pass all tests (19/19 pgcl-test + 11-13/13
pgcl-stress + 16/16 mm-selftests) with zero Oops/WARN.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>
